[[File:TurkSColes.jpg|right|thumb|Gaughan's reconstructed Turk]]'''John Gaughan''' (born 1940) is an American manufacturer of [[Magic (illusion)|magic]] acts and equipment for [[Magician (illusion)|magicians]] based in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]. His style of work is classic, not based heavily on machinery and technology.

Great illusionists have noted his work, such as [[David Blaine]], who has several times called him "a magical genius".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/18/fashion/18magic.html |title=Magicians Ask: What’s Up His Sleeve? |work=nytimes.com |accessdate=October 8, 2009 |first=Stephanie |last=Rosenbloom |date=May 18, 2008}}</ref>

He has built for people such as [[Alan Wakeling]], [[Mark Wilson (magician)|Mark Wilson]], [[Criss Angel]], [[David Copperfield (illusionist)|David Copperfield]], David Blaine, [[Simon Drake]], [[Doug Henning]] and [[The Doors]], and is responsible for the construction of dozens of major acts. He also has constructed a replica of the 18th century [[chess]]-playing machine, [[The Turk]], which often tours chess conferences.

Gaughan created [[David Copperfield's flying illusion]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yuddy.com/celebrity/david-copperfield/bio |title=David Copperfield Bio |work=yuddy.com |accessdate=July 4, 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081122093530/http://www.yuddy.com/celebrity/david-copperfield/bio |archivedate=November 22, 2008 |df= }}</ref> which is notable for its graceful motion and unencumbered appearance. Gaughan holds a patent on a method for creating the illusion of flight.<ref>{{US patent reference 
 | number = 5354238
 | y = 1994
 | m = 10
 | d = 11
 | inventor = John Gaughan
 | title = Levitation Apparatus
}}
</ref> Gaughan also created a "one-of-a-kind" prop for Mark Wilson Productions for a National Fire Prevention Week Event. Using a standard golf cart chassis, John and his team created "Snuffy". Snuffy was a "magical" boiler type [[fire engine]] that seemed to drive along without any visible driver.

